&startq;don't you think I am, Indiana?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Me, brother? la! I'm &s;ure I think &s;he's the $glie&s;t
little fright, poor thing! I ever &s;aw in the world, poor
thing! &s;uch a little, &s;hort, dumpty, hump backed,
crooked, limping figure of a fright&mdash;poor thing!&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Yes, yes,&endq; cried he, changing his po&s;ture, but
&s;till undauntedly examining him&s;elf before the gla&s;s,
&startq;he has taken amazing care of me, I confe&s;s; matched
me mo&s;t exactly!&endq;</P>
<P>Then &s;itting down, as if to con&s;ider the matter more
&s;eriou&s;ly, he took Indiana by the arm, and, with &s;ome
di&s;plea&s;ure, &s;aid, &startq;Why, what does the old quoz
