have been taken for her, even without change of dre&s;s;
but the effect produced upon the beholders bore not the
&s;ame parallel: what in her was beauty in its highe&s;t
delicacy, in him &s;eemed effeminacy in its lowe&s;t de|gradation.
The brilliant fairne&s;s of his fore-head, the
tran&s;parent pink of his cheeks, th$ pouting vermillion
of his lips, the liquid lu&s;tre of his langui&s;hing blue
